## 3. STORED CROSS-SITE SCRIPTING (XSS)

**Title:** Stored XSS in Comments with Inadequate Sanitization  
**CVSS Score:** 7.3 (High)  
**CWE:** CWE-79  
**OWASP:** A07:2021 – Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)  

### Description

The comments endpoint accepts arbitrary HTML content and stores it in the database. While the client-side JavaScript attempts to filter `<script>` tags, this is easily bypassed using alternative XSS vectors (event handlers, iframes, SVG, etc.). The Handlebars template uses triple braces `{{{body}}}` which renders HTML without escaping.

**Vulnerable Code Locations:**
- `src/main/java/com/scalesec/vulnado/CommentsController.java` (Line 22)
- `client/index.html` (Line 73)
- `client/js/index.js` (Line 22-30)

**Backend Accepts Any Comment:**
```java
@CrossOrigin(origins = "*")
@RequestMapping(value = "/comments", method = RequestMethod.POST, 
                produces = "application/json", 
                consumes = "application/json")
Comment createComment(@RequestHeader(value="x-auth-token") String token, 
                     @RequestBody CommentRequest input) {
  return Comment.create(input.username, input.body);
}
```

**Frontend Inadequate Filter:**
```javascript
if (comment.body.indexOf("<script>") < 0) {
  $("#comments-container").append(template(comment));
}
```

**Template (Unescaped):**
```html
<p class="card-text">{{{body}}}</p>
```

### Impact

- **Session Hijacking:** Steal authentication tokens from localStorage
- **Credential Theft:** Capture login information via fake login forms
- **Malware Distribution:** Inject malicious scripts affecting all users viewing page
- **Website Defacement:** Modify page content for specific users
- **Keylogging:** Record user input (passwords, messages, etc.)
- **Phishing:** Redirect users to attacker's site
- **Worm Propagation:** Self-replicating payload infects all users

### Mitigation

1. **Output Encoding:** Use proper escaping based on context (HTML, JavaScript, CSS, URL)
2. **Content Security Policy (CSP):** Restrict script sources and inline scripts
3. **Server-side Sanitization:** Clean HTML using OWASP ESAPI or similar library
4. **HTTPOnly Cookies:** Store authentication tokens in HTTPOnly, Secure cookies
5. **Input Length Limits:** Restrict comment size to prevent payloads
6. **Use Security Headers:** X-Content-Type-Options, X-Frame-Options, X-XSS-Protection

**Java Remediation:**
```java
import org.owasp.html.HtmlPolicyBuilder;
import org.owasp.html.HtmlSanitizer;
import org.owasp.html.PolicyFactory;

public static String sanitizeHtml(String input) {
  PolicyFactory policy = new HtmlPolicyBuilder()
    .allowElements("b", "i", "em", "strong", "p", "br")
    .allowAttributes("class").onElements("p")
    .toFactory();
  return HtmlSanitizer.sanitize(input, policy);
}
```

**JavaScript Remediation:**
```javascript
// Use textContent instead of innerHTML
const commentDiv = document.createElement('p');
commentDiv.textContent = comment.body;  // Safe - no HTML injection

// Or use DOMPurify library
const sanitized = DOMPurify.sanitize(comment.body);
```

### Steps to Reproduce

1. Log into application at `http://localhost:1337`
2. Navigate to comments section
3. Enter XSS payload in comment field
4. Submit comment
5. Reload page or view as different user
6. Payload executes in browser

