## 8. MISSING CSRF PROTECTION

**Title:** No Cross-Site Request Forgery Token Protection  
**CVSS Score:** 6.5 (Medium)  
**CWE:** CWE-352  
**OWASP:** A01:2021 – Broken Access Control  

### Description

The application does not implement CSRF tokens on state-changing requests (POST, PUT, DELETE). Combined with `@CrossOrigin(origins = "*")`, attackers can forge requests from other domains.

**Vulnerable Code Locations:**
- `src/main/java/com/scalesec/vulnado/LoginController.java` (Line 16)
- `src/main/java/com/scalesec/vulnado/CommentsController.java` (Line 14, 21, 27)

```java
@CrossOrigin(origins = "*")  // Allows any origin
@RequestMapping(value = "/login", method = RequestMethod.POST, ...)
LoginResponse login(@RequestBody LoginRequest input) {
  // No CSRF token validation!
}

@CrossOrigin(origins = "*")  // Allows any origin
@RequestMapping(value = "/comments", method = RequestMethod.POST, ...)
Comment createComment(@RequestHeader(value="x-auth-token") String token, 
                     @RequestBody CommentRequest input) {
  // No CSRF token validation!
}
```

### Impact

- **Malicious Comment Posting:** Attacker posts on behalf of authenticated user
- **Account Actions:** Delete comments, modify profile
- **Email Verification Bypass:** Change email on user account
- **Financial Transactions:** If application handles payments
- **Defacement:** Comments section filled with attacker content
- **Reputation Damage:** User accounts appear to perform malicious actions

### Mitigation

1. **Implement CSRF Tokens:** Double-submit pattern or synchronizer token
2. **Set SameSite Cookies:** Prevent automatic cookie inclusion in cross-site requests
3. **Remove @CrossOrigin(*):** Restrict to specific trusted domains
4. **Validate Origin Header:** Ensure request from legitimate source
5. **Use State-Safe Methods:** GET for retrieval, POST/DELETE for modifications

**Remediation Code:**

```java
// Spring Security CSRF configuration
@Configuration
@EnableWebSecurity
public class SecurityConfig extends WebSecurityConfigurerAdapter {
  
  @Override
  protected void configure(HttpSecurity http) throws Exception {
    http
      .csrf()  // Enable CSRF protection (default in Spring Security)
        .csrfTokenRepository(CookieCsrfTokenRepository.withHttpOnlyFalse())
      .and()
      .authorizeRequests()
        .antMatchers("/login").permitAll()
        .anyRequest().authenticated()
      .and()
      .cors()  // Configure CORS properly
        .configurationSource(corsConfigurationSource());
  }
  
  @Bean
  public CorsConfigurationSource corsConfigurationSource() {
    CorsConfiguration configuration = new CorsConfiguration();
    configuration.setAllowedOrigins(Arrays.asList("https://trusted-domain.com"));
    configuration.setAllowedMethods(Arrays.asList("GET", "POST", "DELETE"));
    configuration.setAllowedHeaders(Arrays.asList("*"));
    configuration.setAllowCredentials(true);
    
    UrlBasedCorsConfigurationSource source = 
      new UrlBasedCorsConfigurationSource();
    source.registerCorsConfiguration("/**", configuration);
    return source;
  }
}

// Frontend: Include CSRF token
@RestController
public class CsrfController {
  @GetMapping("/csrf-token")
  public CsrfToken csrfToken(CsrfToken token) {
    return token;
  }
}
```

